      Installing The Framework [10 ms]

      Scenarios 1 2 0 
      As a developer
You can leverage xBDD within your .Net testing projects
By installing the xBDD.Core nuget package

      1. 2 If You Use An MS Test Project [0 ms]

        1. Then you create an MSTest project by following the directions here: https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/core/testing/unit-testing-with-mstest [0 ms]
        2. And you can install xBDD by executing: [Input] [0 ms] 
          dotnet add package xBDD

    2. 3
      Executing Your First Scenario [78,027 ms]

      Scenarios 2 0 0 
      As a developer
You can automate a basic scenario
By using xB.AddScenario and the Given, When, Then, and And operations.

      1. 3 Running A Success Web UI Test [48,236 ms]

        1. Given you code the following feature definition: [Input] [0 ms] 
          namespace Amazon.Features.SearchingProducts
{
    using Microsoft.VisualStudio.TestTools.UnitTesting;
    using System;
    using System.Threading.Tasks;
    using xBDD;
    using xBDD.Browser;

	[TestClass]
	[AsA("anonymous user")]
	[YouCan("search across all amazon products")]
	[By("using primary search bar on the home page")]
	public class SearchingAllProducts: IFeature
	{
		private User you = new User();
		public IOutputWriter OutputWriter { get; private set; }

		public SearchingAllProducts()
		{
			OutputWriter = new TestContextWriter();
		}
		
		[TestMethod]
		public async Task SearchWithSearchButton()
		{
			await xB.AddScenario(this)
				.Given(you.NavigateTo("the amazon home page","https://www.amazon.com"))
				.When(you.EnterTheText("echo").In("the search box", "#twotabsearchtextbox"))
				.And(you.Click("the search button", "input[type=submit]"))
				.Then(you.WillSee("the search results section", "#s-results-list-atf").IsVisible())
				.Run();
		}
	}
}
        2. When you run the MS Test Project with the following command: [Input] [Output] [48,213 ms] 
          dotnet test -v n --filter FullyQualifiedName=Amazon.Features.SearchingProducts.SearchingAllProducts.SearchWithSearchButton

          namespace Amazon.Features.SearchingProducts
{
    using Microsoft.VisualStudio.TestTools.UnitTesting;
    using System;
    using System.Threading.Tasks;
    using xBDD;
    using xBDD.Browser;

	[TestClass]
	[AsA("anonymous user")]
	[YouCan("search across all amazon products")]
	[By("using primary search bar on the home page")]
	public class SearchingAllProducts_Failing: IFeature
	{
		private User you = new User();
		public IOutputWriter OutputWriter { get; private set; }

		public SearchingAllProducts_Failing()
		{
			OutputWriter = new TestContextWriter();
		}
		
		[TestMethod]
		public async Task SearchWithSearchButton_Failing()
		{
			await xB.AddScenario(this)
				.Given(you.NavigateTo("the amazon home page","https://www.amazon.com"))
				.When(you.EnterTheText("echo").In("the search box", "#twotabsearchtextbox"))
				.And(you.Click("the search button", "input[type=submit]"))
				.Then(you.WillSee("the search results section", "#BAD_SELECTOR").IsVisible())
				.Run();
		}
	}
}

      4. 0 Html With Preview [Skipped - Not Started] [0 ms]

      5. 0 Collapse [Skipped - Not Started] [0 ms]

      6. 0 Collapse All [Skipped - Not Started] [0 ms]

      7. 0 Expand [Skipped - Not Started] [0 ms]

      8. 0 Expand All [Skipped - Not Started] [0 ms]

  5. 5
    Generate Reports - Customize Html Report [8,623 ms]

    Features 3 0 0
    Scenarios 9 0 0

    1. 25
      Write Failures Only [786 ms]

      Scenarios 3 0 0 
      As a Developer
You can set the html report to only report on failures
By passing the report writer a true value for the failuresOnly parameter.

      1. 3 Passing [314 ms]

        1. Given the test results of a single passing scenario set to report only failures [6 ms]
        2. When you navigate to the test html report with a single passing scenario [264 ms]
        3. Then you will see the test run areas list is not there [42 ms]

      2. 3 Skipped [144 ms]

        1. Given the test results of a single skipped scenario set to only report on failures [4 ms]
        2. When you navigate to the test html report with a single skipped scenario [117 ms]
        3. Then you will see the test run areas list is not there [22 ms]

      3. 3 Failing [318 ms]

        1. Given the test results of a full test run with all outcomes set to only report on failures [24 ms]
        2. When you navigate to the test html report with a single failed scenario [188 ms]
        3. Then you will see the step 2 with red badge is visible because the step failed and the report will be expanded to the failed step [105 ms]

    2. 26
      Shorten Area Name [4,720 ms]

      Scenarios 3 0 0 
      As a Developer
You can shorten the area name in the Html report.
By shorten the area name by removing the beginning of the name that matches a provided string

      1. 4 Matches Start Of Area Name [3,716 ms]

        1. Given the test results of a single passing scenario set to skip the string 'My ' in the area name [7 ms]
        2. When you navigate to the test html report with a single passing scenario [3,112 ms]
        3. Then you will see the area title line is visible [229 ms]
        4. And you will see the area title line has text 'Area 1' [366 ms]

      2. 4 Matches None Of Area Name [575 ms]

        1. Given the test results of a single passing scenario set to skip the string 'No Match' in the area name [8 ms]
        2. When you navigate to the test html report with a single passing scenario [319 ms]
        3. Then you will see the area title line is visible [96 ms]
        4. And you will see the area title line has text 'My Area 1' [150 ms]

      3. 4 Matches All Of Area Name [420 ms]

        1. Given the test results of a single passing scenario set to skip the string 'My Area 1' in the area name [16 ms]
        2. When you navigate to the test html report with a single passing scenario [206 ms]
        3. Then you will see the area title line is visible [69 ms]
        4. And you will see the area title line has text '[Missing! (or Full Name Skipped)]' [124 ms]

    3. 27
      Sort Test Run Results [3,106 ms]

      Scenarios 3 0 0 
      As a Developer
You can control the order test results are rendered
By calling the SortTestRunResults method on the test run: 'xB.CurrentRun.SortTestRunResults' before running the html report

      1. 4 Not Sorted [767 ms]

        1. Given a sample executed test run that is not sorted [41 ms]
        2. When you navigate to the sample test html report that is not sorted [323 ms]
        3. Then you will see the feature name has text 'Sample All Outcome Feature' because it was the first feature alphabetically [187 ms]
        4. And you will see the scenario name has text 'Failed Scenario' because it is the first scenario alphabetically [214 ms]

      2. 5 Sorted [1,245 ms]

        1. Given a sample executed test run that is not sorted [49 ms]
        2. When you navigate to the sample test html report that is sorted [235 ms]
        3. And you click when the feature name is visible [604 ms]
        4. Then you will see the feature name has text 'Sample Passing Feature' because it was the first in the feature sort [Output] [174 ms]

      3. 5 Partially Sorted [1,085 ms]

      12. 3 Write Run Scenario With Step With Multiline Parameter [15 ms]

        1. Given you code the following feature definition: [Input] [10 ms] 
          using System.Threading.Tasks;
using xBDD.Features;
namespace xBDD.Features.GenerateReports.GenerateTextReport.WriteToTextScenarios
{
    public class RunScenarioWithStepWithMultilineParameter : IExecute<string>
    {
        public async Task<string> Execute()
        {
            var xBDD = new xBDDMock();
            xBDD.CurrentRun.TestRun.Name = "My Test Run";
            await xBDD.CurrentRun
                .AddScenario("My Scenario", "My Feature", "My.Area.Path")
                .Given(xBDD.CreateStep("my starting condition with the following", (s) => { }, $"My{System.Environment.NewLine}multiline{System.Environment.NewLine}parameter"))
                .When(xBDD.CreateStep("my action"))
                .Then(xBDD.CreateStep("my ending condition"))
                .Run();
            return await xBDD.CurrentRun.TestRun.WriteToText();
        }
    }
}
